<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-185-329 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 597 935</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  April 1 1991 v220 n13 p34(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The crisis in Africa. (telecommunications infrastructure) (CoverStory)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Williamson, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Africa has a poor telecommunications infrastructure, and someregions have even experienced negative growth intelecommunications since the mid-1980s.andP;  Some 12 percent of theworld's population resides in Africa, but the country has only 1.4percent of the world's telephone lines.andP;  The average telephonepenetration is .7 lines per 100 people, compared to 50 to 80 linesper 100 people in developed countries.andP;  The poor infrastructureincreases the inequalities in opportunity, increases risk, andnegatively affects economic activity.andP;  The reasons for the lack ofa basic telecommunications infrastructure include the government'slack of attention to telecommunications, and the lack of localparticipation in the design and manufacture of telecommunicationsequipment.andP;  Privatization, deregulation, and liberalization oftelecommunications have not received much support from the public,but the improvement in Africa's telecommunications infrastructureis essential for the survival of the country.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Telecommunications ServicesPolicyTelephone SystemsGovernment RegulationEconomicsCommunications IndustryAfrica.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablephotograph.andO;Caption:   African telecommunications: today and tomorrow. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>